rogress\n\n=C2=A0 \nNamaste f=\r\nriends,\n=C2=A0\nThis is a small writeup on &quot;siddhis&quot; vis-a-vis spiritual pro=\r\ngress, in reaction \nto further exchanges on Twitter. This is a delicate are=\r\na where many have \nmisconceptions and I will try to address them.\n=C2=A0\n*=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nMaharshi Vasishtha&#39;s teaching to Lord Rama is clear i=\r\nn Yoga Vaasishtham. The \ngoal of existence and sadhana is self-realization.=\r\n Siddhis are to be neither \nspecifically sought nor specifically avoided, b=\r\ny a seeker of Self. If Nature \ngives one some siddhi(s), one should accept =\r\nthem with neither excitement nor \ndisappointment. But one should NOT run af=\r\nter them, for they are neither \nnecessary nor sufficient for self-realizati=\r\non and liberation.\n=C2=A0\nVivekananda used the same principle when Ramakiri=\r\nshna proposed to give his \nsiddhis to Vivekananda. He asked whether the sid=\r\ndhis will enable him to realize \ngod. Ramakrishna said no. Vivekananda firm=\r\nly declined the offer then! Of course, \nwhen Ramakrishna gave them anyway l=\r\nater, he accepted them. Vivekananda&#39;s two \nactions demonstrate Vasishtha&#39;s =\r\ninstructions well.\n=C2=A0\n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nLet us use the analogy of =\r\nclimbing a hill. Climbing hill is one&#39;s spiritual \nsadhana. Reaching the to=\r\np is liberation. Different people climb the hill from \ndifferent sides and =\r\nusing different paths. There may be trees with nice fruits \non the sides of=\r\n the road. They are siddhis or special abilities.\n=C2=A0\nIf one gets distra=\r\ncted, starts climbing the trees and collecting fruits, one&#39;s \njourney gets =\r\ndelayed and one may not reach the top. That is why Vasishtha says a \nseeker=\r\n of Self does not pursue any siddhis.\n=C2=A0\nBut if some fruits fall in one=\r\n&#39;s lap by themselves, one can keep them. \nSimilarly, siddhis that come to o=\r\nne by themselves can be accepted by a seeker of \nSelf.\n=C2=A0\nNow an import=\r\nant distinction:\n=C2=A0\nThere are some trees that are found at lower altitu=\r\ndes also, but some really \nspecial trees are found at very high altitudes o=\r\nnly. If one has such a fruit, it \nshows that one has climbed great heights.=\r\n Similarly, some siddhis do not mean \nmuch, but some siddhis are very speci=\r\nal and only really elevated sadhakas can \nobtain them (whether by trying or=\r\n without trying). If a sadhakas demonstrates \nsuch a siddhi, you can see th=\r\nat one progressed a lot. However, the key is that \none who climbed the same=\r\n or more distance may not have that or any other fruit. \n\n=C2=A0\n*=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nUnlike in the example of climbing hill, which is an external a=\r\nctivity, spiritual \nprogress in real life is *internal*. There is NO way fo=\r\nr anyone to know for sure \nhow much progress one has made, how much self-co=\r\nntrol one has internally and \nwhat exactly goes on in one&#39;s mind. We may tr=\r\ny to judge it from external factors \nsuch as actions, words etc, but it is =\r\nnot necessarily accurate.\n=C2=A0\nHere, some people swayed by siddhis may be=\r\n tempted to use one&#39;s siddhis to judge \nhow high one climbed. But that is f=\r\naulty. One person who reached the absolute \ntop may not have any fruits, wh=\r\nile one person who still has ways to climb may \nhave gotten some really nic=\r\ne fruit. Using externaslly demonstrable siddhis that \nare neither necessary=\r\n nor sufficient for Self-realization as a measure of one&#39;s \nprogress is uns=\r\nound.\n=C2=A0\nGiven that spiritual progress is internal, how can we judge it=\r\n and compare \npeople then? Well, we need not and should not. Only a sarvaan=\r\ntaryaami - a \nperfected being who has access to each being&#39;s internal state=\r\n - can do that.\n=C2=A0\n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nRajarshi, you are assuming th=\r\nat Ramakrishna Paramahamsa is a Paramahamsa on \nVimalananda&#39;s scale. You ar=\r\ne concluding that Ramakrishna is a Paramahamsa; \nAbhedananda, Vivekananda e=\r\ntc are lower than that; Vimalananda is a rishi; and \nhence Vimalananda is s=\r\nuperior to Abhedananda and Vivekananda by 2pwr16 to 2.\n=C2=A0\nIs Paramahams=\r\na Nithyananda, who was caught in a sex scandal, also a Paramahamsa \nbecause=\r\n he is known so? See, how people are famously known may or may not \nreflect=\r\n their spiritual stature. Real spiritual stature is internal and you \ncanno=\r\nt see it.\n=C2=A0\nWe do not know who Ramakrishna Paramahamsa really is. He m=\r\nay not be just a \nparamahamsa on Vimalananda&#39;s scale, but be a siddha or a =\r\nnatha or even a rishi. \nHe may even be Vishnu himself, as he himself said a=\r\nnd some religious experts of \nthat time declared based on various signs. If=\r\n Ramakrishna Paramahamsa is Vishnu \nhimself, Vivekananda, Abhedananda etc c=\r\nan definitely be rishis or naths in \nVimalananda&#39;s scale. If your argument =\r\nis that they cannot be because they did \nnot demonstrate siddhis compatible=\r\n with that status, that is a non-point as I \nexplained above. The disagreem=\r\nent between then boils down a difference in the \nrelevance and importance o=\r\nf externally demonstrated siddhis.\n=C2=A0\n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nWhy this =\r\nis relevant and I spent some time on this is that some people seem to \nhave=\r\n misconceptions. The take home for some people from some books describing \n=\r\nmiracles and siddhis may be that siddhis are important.\n=C2=A0\nVasishtha is=\r\n not only a rishi, but one of saptarshis. Please read what he taught \nLord =\r\nRama in Yoga Vaasishtham. It is the essence of Veda and Upanishad. It will =\r\n\nbalance your views and mould your attitude. Read Yoga Vaasishtham. Siddhis=\r\n are \nneither necessary nor sufficient for self-realization. Don&#39;t be distr=\r\nacted by \nthem or be infatuated with them.\n=C2=A0\nThe goal of sadhana is th=\r\nat your notions of &quot;this is I and these are mine&quot; get \nsubtler and subtler =\r\nand hold of six internal enemies on you becomes weaker and \nweaker. Others =\r\nmay or may not be able to see and judge your progress, but you \nknow your p=\r\nrogress and weaknesses the best. THAT is the crux and siddhis have no \nrele=\r\nvance or meaning. Any fascination for them will set you back in your \nsadha=\r\nna.\n=C2=A0\nBest regards,\nNarasimha\n----------------------------------------=\r\n---------------------------\n=C2=A0 Free Jyotish Software, Free Jyotish Less=\r\nons, Jyotish Writings,\n&quot;Do It Yourself&quot; ritual manuals for short Homam and =\r\nPitri Tarpana:\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 http://www.VedicAstrologer.org\n=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 Films that make a difference: http://SaraswatiFilm=\r\ns.org\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 Spirituality: http://groups.yahoo.com/group/=\r\nvedic-wisdom\n=C2=A0 Jyotish writings: http://groups.yahoo.com/group/Jyotish=\r\nWritings\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 Twitter ID: @homam10=\r\n8\n-------------------------------------------------------------------\n=C2=\r\n=A0\n--- In vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com, Narasimha PVR Rao &lt;pvr@...&gt; wrote:=\r\n\n&gt;\n&gt; Namaste friends,\n&gt; \n&gt; There was a long friendly ;-) exchange between R=\r\najarshi and me on Friday \n&gt; (July 29) on twitter on measuring spiritual cal=\r\niber. This came from the \n&gt; context of Rajarshi&#39;s comments on the &quot;maturity=\r\n&quot; & &quot;errors&quot; of \n&gt; Ramakrishna&#39;s disciples (regarding their attitude toward=\r\ns Tantra). He \n&gt; compared them with Vimalananda and said their spiritual ca=\r\nliber was of \n&gt; the scale of 2, while Vimalananda&#39;s was 2 power 16. He also=\r\n talked about \n&gt; the hierarchy of spiritual caliber mentioned by V. I want =\r\nto share 2 \n&gt; cents of musings on that.\n&gt; \n&gt; ------------------------------=\r\n-\n&gt; Measuring Spiritual Caliber\n&gt; \n&gt; Rajarshi, here are a few comments on y=\r\nour statements a couple of days \n&gt; back on Twitter comparing spiritual cali=\r\nber. We can&#39;t even compare \n&gt; flowers like hibiscus, rose, jasmine, mogra, =\r\nkewda, lotus etc & say \n&gt; which is a better flower. They have different pro=\r\nperties like color, \n&gt; size, shape, number of petals, type/intensity of sme=\r\nll etc. Relative \n&gt; values depend on the purpose and they cannot be quantif=\r\nied universally. \n&gt; How can any sane person then say that spiritual caliber=\r\n of different \n&gt; people can be compared and quanitified? The field of duali=\r\nty has \n&gt; infinite variety and the [self-]control of a yogi has infinite as=\r\npects \n&gt; to it. You cannot quantify the spiritual caliber of a person as on=\r\ne \n&gt; number and compare them.\n&gt; \n&gt; Before one even attempts to understand V=\r\nimalananda&#39;s order (Paramahamsa \n&gt; &lt; Siddha &lt; Natha &lt; Rishi), please note t=\r\nhat different hierarchies exist \n&gt; in scriptures for deities also. Some con=\r\nsider a hierarchy of deities \n&gt; where Vishnu is supreme. Some consider a hi=\r\nerarchy of deities where \n&gt; Shiva is supreme. Some consider a hierarchy of =\r\ndeities where Shakti is \n&gt; supreme. And so on. None of them is absolute. Al=\r\nl of them are relative \n&gt; and for specific purposes, i.e. from a specific p=\r\nerspective. There are \n&gt; people who take them as absolute and argue that so=\r\n and so thing taught \n&gt; by Vishnu is superior to so and so thing taught by =\r\nShiva, etc. But we \n&gt; know that none of the hierarchies is absolute.\n&gt; \n&gt; O=\r\nne who has the nerve to think that one can compare the wisdom of \n&gt; Jnanesh=\r\nwar, dispassion of Ramana Maharshi, mad devotion of Ramakrishna \n&gt; Paramaha=\r\nmsa, detached activism of Vivekananda, compassion of Shirdi Sai, \n&gt; spiritu=\r\nal ecstasy of Vama Khepa, inner clarity of Lahiri Mahashaya, \n&gt; detachment =\r\nof Trilinga Swami, purity of Tukaram, humility of Eknath \n&gt; Maharaj, ecstat=\r\nic love of Meera Bai, motherly love of Gopaler Ma, etc, \n&gt; is a fool of the=\r\n highest order. They can be compared from specific \n&gt; limited perspectives.=\r\n In one thing, Tukaram may be superior to all, in \n&gt; another Jnaneshwar, in=\r\n another Trilinga, in another Ramakrishna, and so \n&gt; on. You cannot compare=\r\n in absolute terms. You should not even try to. \n&gt; You should just apprecia=\r\nte them individually and aspire to be like any \n&gt; of them that you like the=\r\n most.\n&gt; \n&gt; Vimalananda&#39;s list may be correct from specific perspective. Mo=\r\nre \n&gt; importantly, his words should make one realize that there is always \n=\r\n&gt; scope for further self-control (and the resulting mastery over the field =\r\n\n&gt; of duality) while one is still embodied. One should never rest and \n&gt; as=\r\npire for better self-control. But taking it as gospel and starting to \n&gt; ju=\r\ndge yogis based on that is unwise. Especially making statements like \n&gt; &quot;Vi=\r\nmalananda is heavier than all RK&#39;s discples put togtr&quot; and thinking \n&gt; that=\r\n something is absolute truth because Vimalananda is assumed to have \n&gt; said=\r\n that (vs someone &quot;lower than him&quot;) is unwise.\n&gt; \n&gt; Even if Vimalananda&#39;s h=\r\nierarchy is absolute and universal, don&#39;t assume \n&gt; that you can judge the =\r\nstature of each yogi accurately. Because \n&gt; Ramakrishna was popularly known=\r\n as a Paramahamsa, is he a Paramahamsa as \n&gt; per Vimalananda&#39;s classificati=\r\non or a siddha or a natha or even a rishi? \n&gt; Or may be a deity? My friend,=\r\n don&#39;t assume you know for sure!!! Based on \n&gt; the details we know, can we =\r\nbe absolutely sure of even Vimalananda&#39;s \n&gt; stature based on his own classi=\r\nfication?\n&gt; \n&gt; You said &quot;Approximating 2 equal to each disciples of ramakri=\r\nshna. 2exp16 \n&gt; =3D say Vimalananda. Basic?&quot; You probably made this stateme=\r\nnt based on \n&gt; what you read and heard of Vimalananda. For the sake of argu=\r\nment, it is \n&gt; not even 100% clear whether he was a real person or an imagi=\r\nned \n&gt; character. Svoboda intentionally (and very wisely!) left the latter =\r\n\n&gt; option open in the preface of his Aghora book!\n&gt; \n&gt; If we MUST compare s=\r\npiritual calibers, one possibility is to use a \n&gt; simpler definition of how=\r\n close one is to liberation as a measure of \n&gt; one&#39;s &quot;spiritual caliber&quot;, R=\r\namakrishna&#39;s disciples fare quite well. RK \n&gt; told Abhedananda that it was =\r\ngoing to be his last birth. Others would be \n&gt; back, but he would be libera=\r\nted. To Yogananda, he said there would be \n&gt; one more birth and he would be=\r\n free forever after that. Vimalananda, on \n&gt; the other hand, had atleast on=\r\ne more birth clearly as he said a body was \n&gt; waiting for him. That way, fo=\r\nrget about &quot;RK&#39;s discples put togtr&quot;, just \n&gt; Abhedananda alone is superior=\r\n to Vimalananda!\n&gt; \n&gt; Again, please note that this is just one definition. =\r\nOne can have many \n&gt; definitions. The key is not to jump to unwise conclusi=\r\nons on any \n&gt; hierarchies and say that &quot;X is weightier than Y and so what h=\r\ne said must \n&gt; be more correct&quot;.\n&gt; \n&gt; People with lopsided understanding of=\r\n scriptures take relative knowledge \n&gt; to be absolute and jump to unwise co=\r\nnclusions. I am afraid some people \n&gt; are doing the same now with &quot;modern s=\r\ncriptures&quot; such as the Aghora \n&gt; books. Don&#39;t fall into the trap of taking =\r\nsomething as gospel or as \n&gt; absolute. Written words are always relative an=\r\nd never absolute. \n&gt; Discriminate relative knowledge using intellect at fir=\r\nst and hopefully \n&gt; using experencial realization later on.\n&gt; \n&gt; More impor=\r\ntantly, while we are still searching for &quot;maturity&quot;, we should \n&gt; not commi=\r\nt the &quot;error&quot; of making negative judgmental comments of greats \n&gt; who did f=\r\nar more sadhana than us and experienced a lot more than us.\n&gt; -------------=\r\n------------------\n&gt; \n&gt; Best regards,\n&gt; Narasimha\n\r\n--0-314976710-1312207818=:44137\r\nContent-Type: text/html; charset=utf-8\r\nContent-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable\r\n\r\n&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;&lt;style type=3D&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;&lt;!-- DIV {margin:0px;} --&gt;&lt;/style&gt;&lt;/he=\r\nad&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;div style=3D&quot;font-family:times new roman, new york, times, serif;=\r\nfont-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV&gt;Dear Narasimha,&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;D=\r\nIV&gt;In the discussion that happened, here is my stand, in case you have not =\r\nunderstood the same properly:&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV&gt;1) He was someth=\r\ning special - which I cannot judge - because Manish says so, and on THIS po=\r\nint I trust Manish&#39;s judgement more than your or mine.&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/D=\r\nIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV&gt;2) Some siddhis&nbsp;as you noted are special. Only very higher le=\r\nvel beings can attain the same. Since the topic of siddhis did come up, Vim=\r\nalananda&#39;s ability to suck up a ton of mercury by Vajroli and bring it out =\r\nfr